    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_5r9jb9yi">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_s4iwgvp2">
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_smf9mh3z">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_rus6om2f">
                    To explore how real-world situations naturally lead to quadratic expressions.
                </p>
            </li>
            
            <li xml:id="auto_d22pgw4i">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_9rr2qg7o">
                    The teacher circulates among the pairs, asking guiding questions about how variables represent unknown quantities, encouraging learners to make connections between the different situations, and bridging learner discoveries to the formal instruction that follows.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <p xml:id="auto_rkl7xhut">
        Quadratic expressions often arise when working with area and geometric situations.
    </p>

    <activity xml:id="auto_jnv6dnx2">
        <title>Design a frame</title>
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_39c3gkj0">
                Imagine you are framing a picture for someone. The picture is 7 cm <m>\times</m> 5 cm, and you want to make a custom wood frame of uniform width <m>x</m> around all four sides. In terms of <m>x</m>:
            </p>
            <image width="90%">
            <shortdescription>Framed picture with dimensions</shortdescription>
            <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]

                % Define colors
                \definecolor{frameColor}{RGB}{220, 220, 220} % Neutral gray
                \definecolor{photoColor}{RGB}{255, 255, 255} % White

                % 1. The Outer Frame (Total Area)
                \draw[thick, fill=frameColor] (-1.5,-1.5) rectangle (8.5,6.5);
                
                % 2. The Inner Photo
                \draw[thick, fill=photoColor] (0,0) rectangle (7,5);
                \node at (3.5, 2.5) {\textbf{5 $\times$ 7 Photo}};

                % 3. Dimension Arrows for the Frame Width (x)
                % Left side x
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;, &gt;=Stealth] (-1.5, 2.5) -- (0, 2.5) node[midway, above] {$x$};
                % Right side x
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;, &gt;=Stealth] (7, 2.5) -- (8.5, 2.5) node[midway, above] {$x$};
                % Top side x
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;, &gt;=Stealth] (3.5, 5) -- (3.5, 6.5) node[midway, right] {$x$};
                % Bottom side x
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;, &gt;=Stealth] (3.5, 0) -- (3.5, -1.5) node[midway, right] {$x$};

                % 4. Total Dimension Labels
                % Total Width label at the bottom
                \draw[decorate, decoration={brace, amplitude=10pt, mirror}] (-1.5,-2) -- (8.5,-2) node[midway, below=10pt] {Total Length = $7 + 2x$};
                
                % Total Length label at the right
                \draw[decorate, decoration={brace, amplitude=10pt}] (9, 6.5) -- (9, -1.5) node[midway, right=10pt] {Total Width = $5 + 2x$};

            \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            </image>
            <ol>
                <li xml:id="auto_jw4sk5bv"><p xml:id="auto_3bdfum3f">What are the widths and height of the framed picture?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_l5n6jux9"><p xml:id="auto_vwfno678">What is the total area of the framed picture?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_4qmb10na"><p xml:id="auto_wdc0wezp">What is the total area of the frame without the picture (in other words, how much wood do you need)?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_t92czsmv"><p xml:id="auto_uygdqe5v">Write each of the expressions in standard form. Geometrically, what does the quadratic, linear and constant terms represent?</p></li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <insight xml:id="auto_873gti79">
        <title>Quadratic expressions describe interacting growth</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_5017imdy">
            Quadratic expressions are not just numbers; they describe multidimensional growth. In many real-life
            situations a quadratic term appears because two independent linear factors interact with each other.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_5sbdn6lt">
            A quadratic expression represents the accumulation of different types of growth in a single system:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li xml:id="auto_5g7ahc6j">
                <p xml:id="auto_xencl7ri">
                    The <m>ax^2</m> term captures the "compounding" or "area" effect where a change in <m>x</m>
                    impacts the result in two directions at once (for example, the four corners of a frame or a
                    change that affects both price and quantity).
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_223oclhq">
                <p xml:id="auto_e1mwgpph">
                    The <m>bx</m> term captures linear growth, where a change in <m>x</m> affects only one dimension
                    (for example, side strips of a frame).
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_324qkvbk">
                <p xml:id="auto_u6o0ul17">
                    The constant term represents the baseline or starting state before any changes were made.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </insight>


    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_vchqri3c">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_4vlttim9">
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_4er3e3em">
                <title>Key Takeaways</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_6xd7i7sk">
                    <ol>
                        <li xml:id="auto_5is0t18m">
                            <p xml:id="auto_jbpuvax6">
                                <alert>When Do We Get Quadratic Expressions?</alert> When we multiply two linear expressions, calculate areas with variable dimensions, find products of consecutive numbers, or work with optimization problems.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_d9bzdogh">
                            <p xml:id="auto_pwbu20hi">
                                <alert>Steps to Form a Quadratic Expression:</alert> Identify the variable <m>\rightarrow</m> write expressions for each quantity <m>\rightarrow</m> multiply using the distributive property <m>\rightarrow</m> expand and combine like terms <m>\rightarrow</m> write in standard form.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_vj0je7gj">
                            <p xml:id="auto_qpa6qona">
                                <alert>Standard Form:</alert> <m>ax^2 + bx + c</m>, where <m>a \neq 0</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_h2y27pk5">
                            <p xml:id="auto_s2d9dcbp">
                                <alert>Real-World Connections:</alert> Area problems, number relationships, business profit, and engineering design.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <paragraphs>
        <title>Conclusion</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_s0k0ti7u">
            In the picture below we can see which parts of the expression correspond to the different areas of the frame. The four corners (yellow) represent the <m>x^2</m> term, the four sides (blue) represent the <m>x</m> term, and the photo (white) represents the constant term:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li xml:id="auto_fmau91ig">Area = <m>4x^2 + 24x + 35</m></li>
            <li xml:id="auto_oyfved77">1 photo: <m>35 \text{ cm}^2</m></li>
            <li xml:id="auto_u74uc5er">4 sides: <m>7x + 7x + 5x + 5x = 24x \text{ cm}^2</m></li>
            <li xml:id="auto_ulnykdx0">4 corners: <m>4x^2 \text{ cm}^2</m></li>    
        </ul>
        <image width="80%">
            <shortdescription>Quadratic expression as area of a framed picture</shortdescription>
        <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]

                % Define colors
                \definecolor{cornerColor}{RGB}{255, 215, 0} % Gold
                \definecolor{sideColor}{RGB}{100, 180, 200}  % Teal-ish
                \definecolor{photoColor}{RGB}{240, 240, 240} % Light Gray

                % 1. The Original Photo (The Constant 'c')
                \fill[photoColor] (0,0) rectangle (7,5);
                \node at (3.5, 2.5) {\textbf{Photo (35)}};
                \draw (0,0) rectangle (7,5);

                % 2. The Side Strips (The Linear Term 'bx')
                % Top and Bottom strips
                \fill[sideColor] (0,5) rectangle (7,6.5);
                \fill[sideColor] (0,0) rectangle (7,-1.5);
                \node at (3.5, 5.75) {$7x$};
                \node at (3.5, -0.75) {$7x$};
                
                % Left and Right strips
                \fill[sideColor] (-1.5,0) rectangle (0,5);
                \fill[sideColor] (7,0) rectangle (8.5,5);
                \node[rotate=90] at (-0.75, 2.5) {$5x$};
                \node[rotate=270] at (7.75, 2.5) {$5x$};

                % 3. The Corners (The Quadratic Term 'ax^2')
                \fill[cornerColor] (-1.5,5) rectangle (0,6.5);   % Top-Left
                \fill[cornerColor] (7,5) rectangle (8.5,6.5);    % Top-Right
                \fill[cornerColor] (-1.5,0) rectangle (0,-1.5);  % Bottom-Left
                \fill[cornerColor] (7,0) rectangle (8.5,-1.5);   % Bottom-Right
                
                \node at (-0.75, 5.75) {$x^2$};
                \node at (7.75, 5.75) {$x^2$};
                \node at (-0.75, -0.75) {$x^2$};
                \node at (7.75, -0.75) {$x^2$};

                % Outlines for clarity
                \draw[dashed] (-1.5,-1.5) grid[step=1.5] (8.5,6.5);
                \draw[thick] (-1.5,-1.5) rectangle (8.5,6.5);

                % Labels for dimensions
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-1.5, 7) -- (0, 7) node[midway, above] {$x$};
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (0, 7) -- (7, 7) node[midway, above] {$7$};
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (7, 7) -- (8.5, 7) node[midway, above] {$x$};
                
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-2.2, 0) -- (-2.2, 5) node[midway, left] {$5$};
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-2.2, 5) -- (-2.2, 6.5) node[midway, left] {$x$};
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-2.2, 0) -- (-2.2, -1.5) node[midway, left] {$x$};

            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
        </image>
    </paragraphs>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_rl6g99qb">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_2ts2dsl3">
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_s3h7b32y">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_t8jyurqv">
                    To practise forming quadratic expressions from real-world contexts.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_rbgosrot">
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_fat2wxcb">
                    Learners work through the following examples:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_dar3w39q">
                    <alert>Example 1:</alert> A garden has a length of <m>(x + 4)</m> metres and a width of <m>(x + 1)</m> metres. Find the area.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_civ8n0qy">
                    Area <m>= (x + 4)(x + 1) = x^2 + 5x + 4</m> square metres.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_r9te1but">
                    <alert>Example 2:</alert> Find the product of two consecutive integers. Let the first integer be <m>x</m>. The next consecutive integer is <m>(x + 1)</m>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_3uffrz8x">
                    Product <m>= x(x + 1) = x^2 + x</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_2uthwdad">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_3lh90665">
                    The teacher monitors learner progress, provides feedback, and supports learners who need additional help.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_hw00bv80">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_237ruyfl">
                A rectangular garden has a length of <m>(x + 4)</m> metres and a width of <m>(x + 1)</m> metres.
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_ejxdtp1e">Form an expression for the area of the garden.</li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ihhkr44z">Write the expression in standard form.</li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_oe1htn12">
                Area of a rectangle:
                <me>
                    \text{Area} = \text{length} \times \text{width}
                </me>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_gn26dnyt">
                Substitute the given expressions:
                <me>
                    (x + 4)(x + 1)
                </me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_jclclu67">
                Expand:
                <me>
                    x^2 + x + 4x + 4
                </me>
                <me>
                    = x^2 + 5x + 4
                </me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_rgoznxpz">
                The area is expressed as a quadratic expression.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-football-home-away">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_iyoi38hh">
                A local football league has <m>n</m> teams. Each pair of teams plays two matches: one at Team A's home ground and one at Team B's home ground. How many matches are played in total? Express your answer as a quadratic expression in <m>n</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_ksjs8sw0">
                Each of the <m>n</m> teams will play <m>n-1</m> matches in its home ground (one against each other team), because there are <m>n-1</m> other teams to play against (a team cannot play itself). So the total number of ordered matches is <m>n(n-1)</m> which expands to <m>n^2 - n</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="auto_mn6u8pyw">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_zz6qu9cl">
                The product of two consecutive integers is formed.
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_ksf1n4en">Represent the integers algebraically.</li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_30qy517f">Form the expression for their product.</li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_3lb7v2if">Write the result in standard form.</li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_aggnu9pa">
                Let the first integer be <m>x</m>.
                The next consecutive integer is <m>x + 1</m>.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_y0otddn6">
                Their product:
                <me>
                    x(x + 1)
                </me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_lfj48rge">
                Expand:
                <me>
                    x^2 + x
                </me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_comyjfe5">
                This is a quadratic expression.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="auto_f5hl2zfg">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_md8p7qkt">
                A farmer wants to build a rectangular pen for goats. She has <m>60</m> metres of fencing 
                and will use an existing wall as one side of the pen. If the width of the pen 
                (perpendicular to the wall) is <m>x</m> metres:
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_e1lyyiss">Express the length of the pen in terms of <m>x</m>.</li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ebhp85pi">Form a quadratic expression for the area of the pen.</li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_lib38nzv">Write the expression in standard form.</li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_7p35ogyz">
                Since the wall forms one side, the farmer only needs fencing for three sides: 
                two widths and one length.
                <md>
                    <mrow>2x + \text{length} \amp= 60</mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{length} \amp= 60 - 2x</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_44j8axpx">
                Finding the area of the rectangular pen:
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Area} \amp= \text{length} \times \text{width}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= (60 - 2x) \times x</mrow>
                    <intertext>Expanding:</intertext>
                    <mrow>\amp= 60x - 2x^2</mrow>
                    <intertext>Writing in standard form (with <m>x^2</m> term first):</intertext>
                    <mrow>\amp= -2x^2 + 60x</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_as32kucn">
                This quadratic expression represents the area of the pen in square metres.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    
